Page 1 of 3 
 
Orthodox and Specialty Tea Auction Manual 
1. Purpose of This Manual 
The East Africa Tea Trade Association will introduce the Orthodox and Specialty teas 
on the Auction platform with effect from the month October 2025.  
This manual is intended to guide producers, brokers, buyers, and other stakeholders 
in the handling, submission, cataloguing, and bidding of Orthodox and Specialty teas 
at the Mombasa Tea Auction. It complements, but does not replace, the formal rules 
and regulations of the Mombasa Tea Auction. 
 
2. Definition of Orthodox and Specialty Teas 
2.1 
Orthodox Tea 
Orthodox tea refers to tea processed using the rolling table manufacturing process 
where the leaf remains whole or slightly broken.  
2.2 
Specialty Teas 
This refers to unique or artisanal teas. 
3. Objectives of Introducing Orthodox/Specialty Teas to Auction 
The introduction of the Orthodox teas in the Mombasa auction is intended to:-  
• 
Have better visibility on the Orthodox and specialty teas available in the 
market and the quantities through the auction catalogue and samples. 
• 
Diversify offerings at the Mombasa Tea Auction in addition to the current CTC 
teas. 
• 
Create a fair and transparent platform for premium and specialty teas 
• 
Support market access for small and medium-scale orthodox producers 
• 
Attract a new class of specialty tea buyers 
• 
Stimulate value addition and product differentiation in the region 
4. Categories of Orthodox Teas 
The following common five categories will apply (producers may use their own terms 
based on leaf size and processing). The following will be the new African Orthodox 
Tea categories at the Mombasa Auction:- 
Category 1-Large Whole leaf  
i. 
OPA 
ii. 
OP1 
iii. 
OP 
iv. 
FOP 
v. 
FOP1 
vi. 
Chinese tea 
Category 2-Medium Whole leaf 
Page 2 of 3 
 
 
i. 
BOP1 
ii. 
Pekoe 
iii. 
Pekoe 1 
iv. 
FP 
Category 3-Broken leaf 
i. 
FBOP1 
ii. 
FBOPF 
iii. 
GFBOP 
iv. 
FBOPF SP 
v. 
BOP 
Category 4-Fannings  
i. 
FOF 
ii. 
GOF 
Category 5: Orthodox – Secondary grades 
5. Auction Procedures for Orthodox/Specialty Teas 
• 
Orthodox teas will be offered through a dedicated auction category as defined 
by the Board. 
• 
Auction days are determined by the Board and announced in advance. 
• 
Orthodox teas will appear in a separate catalogue. 
6. Sampling and Sample Request Protocol 
• 
Orthodox teas will be sampled once. A 2kg or 1kg representative sample 
shall be provided by the producer to the broker for a lot size of 20 packages 
and 10 packages respectively. No further sampling shall be permitted, 
including in the event of reprints. 
• 
Samples will be distributed only to buyers who formally request them 
through the broker once the catalogue is published. This will be done through 
an email request to the Broker clearly stating ‘Request for Orthodox 
Samples’ 
• 
The broker is responsible for confirming buyer interest before dispatching 
samples. 
• 
The sample sent by the brokers to the buyers shall not exceed 30grammes for 
each buyer. 
7. Packaging and Labeling Guidelines 
• 
For Orthodox the lot size will be 20 packages. For special teas manufactured 
under orthodox the lot size will be 10 packages or 20 packages.  
• 
Packages must be clearly marked as Orthodox/Specialty to distinguish them 
from CTC teas. 
Page 3 of 3 
 
• 
The Labels should include, Invoice number, Grade, Net weight, Producer 
name/code, date of manufacture and Any certification marks (e.g., Organic, 
Rainforest Alliance), Country of origin 
8. Storage and Handling  
• 
Orthodox teas must be warehoused in Mombasa two working days prior to 
the auction, as per updated Rule 12. 
• 
Teas should be stored in a way that prevents contamination or deterioration. 
• 
Brokers must ensure Orthodox teas are handled separately from CTC to 
preserve identity and quality. 
9. Evaluation Standards 
Orthodox teas been sold at the auction shall be evaluated using their processing style.  
The Board shall define and periodically review these standards to ensure consistency, 
transparency, and fairness in the evaluation and bidding process. 
Buyers and brokers are encouraged to familiarize themselves with these parameters 
and provide feedback to the Board during periodic reviews. 
10. Payment 
Buyers shall remit payment for Orthodox and Specialty teas purchased through the 
auction platform in accordance with the prevailing auction settlement procedures 
established by the Association.

zip_attachments_content.WEATHER - UPTO 9TH SEPTEMBER 2025.docx:
CENTRELINE TEA BROKERS LIMITED MOMBASA


THE KENYA CROP AND WEATHER WEEK UPTO  9TH SEPTEMBER 2025
EAST OF RIFT
KIAMBU/MURANGA/NYERI/MERU/KIRINYAGA
Rainfall was recorded over several parts of this region.
Intermittent cloudiness was experienced in the mornings giving way to sunny intervals. Occasional afternoon showers were experienced over few places. Nights were partly cloudy with showers over few places. 
Both daytime (maximum) and night-time (minimum) temperatures increased over most stations.

                Crop harvest slightly increased.

WEST OF RIFT
NANDI/KERICHO/BOMET/KAKAMEGA/KISII
Most parts of the Highlands West of the Rift valley and Lake Victoria Basin received rainfall.
Morning rains were experienced over few places. Afternoon showers and thunderstorms occurred over few places, occasionally spreading to several places. Few places received night showers. 
Both daytime (maximum) and night-time (minimum) temperatures increased over most stations.

                 Crop harvest increased.                                                                                                                                                                                                  
                                                                                  

                                                                                                                                                                        9TH SEPTEMBER 2025
